FULL OUTER JOIN in SQL

FULL OUTER JOIN is used to retrieve all records from both tables based on a common column.
- If there is a match, the matching records are returned.
- If there is no match in either table, NULL values are returned for the missing side.

Syntax


SELECT column1, column2, ...
FROM table1
FULL OUTER JOIN table2
ON table1.common_column = table2.common_column;


Example

Employee Table

| emp_id | emp_name | dept_id |
| ------ | -------- | ------- |
| 1      | Hitesh   | 101     |
| 2      | Rahul    | 102     |
| 3      | Amit     | 103     |
| 4      | Neha     | 105     |

Department Table

| dept_id | dept_name |
| ------- | --------- |
| 101     | IT        |
| 102     | HR        |
| 103     | Finance   |
| 104     | Sales     |

Query

SELECT
    e.emp_id,
    e.emp_name,
    d.dept_name
FROM Employee e
FULL OUTER JOIN Department d
ON e.dept_id = d.dept_id;


 Output

| emp_id | emp_name | dept_name |
| ------ | -------- | --------- |
| 1      | Hitesh   | IT        |
| 2      | Rahul    | HR        |
| 3      | Amit     | Finance   |
| 4      | Neha     | NULL      |
| NULL   | NULL     | Sales     |

Explanation:

- Matching records from both Employee and Department tables are returned.
- Neha (dept_id = 105) has no matching department, so `dept_name` is NULL.
- Sales (dept_id = 104) has no matching employee, so `emp_id` and `emp_name` are NULL.

> Note:  
> - FULL OUTER JOIN is supported in databases like PostgreSQL, SQL Server, and Oracle.
> - MySQL does not support FULL OUTER JOIN directly.

FULL OUTER JOIN in MySQL

It can be achieved using LEFT JOIN + RIGHT JOIN + UNION:


SELECT
    e.emp_id,
    e.emp_name,
    d.dept_name
FROM Employee e
LEFT JOIN Department d
ON e.dept_id = d.dept_id

UNION

SELECT
    e.emp_id,
    e.emp_name,
    d.dept_name
FROM Employee e
RIGHT JOIN Department d
ON e.dept_id = d.dept_id;
